<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>POWER STEERING GEAR: SHEPPARD M-SERIES - PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE - SECTOR SHAFT SEAL REPLACEMENT</stitle>
    <svcsection/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="pm" graphiccount="14">
        <title>SECTOR SHAFT SEAL REPLACEMENT</title>
        <svcprocinfo>
            <para>Replacement of sector shaft seals requires the gear to be partially disassembled. Should the sector
                shaft need to be replaced, the steering gear must be timed before reassembly.
            </para>
        </svcprocinfo>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Disassemble</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Park the vehicle on a clean, dry, solid surface, preferably concrete. Set the parking
                    brake and block the wheels. Place the transmission in neutral.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Tilt the hood or cab.</para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the pitman arm. Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s05015y_X0501515.xml" xrefid="x0501515">PITMAN ARM</hotlnk>section.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the rubber boot from the sector shaft, and retain for reassembly (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501532">Figure 32</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0501532" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/G05002a2.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 32. Removing Rubber Boot</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a 1/4 inch Allen wrench to remove the dirt shield from the frame side of the sector
                    shaft (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501533">Figure 33</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0501533" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/G05002a0.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 33. Removing Dirt Shield</caption>
            </figure>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>It may be necessary to loosen the steering gear mounting bolts to gain access to the frame
                        side dirt shield.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the sector shaft cover bolts. Carefully separate the sector shaft cover from the
                    housing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501534">Figure 34</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0501534" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501534.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 34. Removing Sector Shaft Cover Bolts</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Pull the sector shaft out of the housing. Remove the seal from the housing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501535">Figure 35</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0501535" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501535.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 35. Removing Seal From Housing</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the sector shaft seal and O-ring from the cover (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501536">Figure 36</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0501536" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501536.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 36. Removing Sector Shaft Seal And O-Ring</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Pry the excluder seal out of the sector shaft cover if equipped (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501537">Figure 37</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0501537" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501537.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 37. Removing Excluder Seal</caption>
            </figure>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Reassemble</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install a new sector shaft seal in the housing. Make sure the blue side of the seal
                    faces toward the outside of the housing (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501538">Figure 38</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>The sector shaft is a two-piece seal. It will be necessary to carefully bend the seal to
                            install it. Once it is in the housing, it may be necessary to work the seal with your
                            fingers or a blunt seal pick so it will sit properly in the groove.
                        </para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0501538" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501538.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 38. Installing Sector Shaft Seal</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install a new sector shaft seal in the cover. Make sure the blue side of the seal faces
                    outward. Install a new O-ring on the cover (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501539">Figure 39</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Coat all seals lightly with clean oil or grease before reassembly.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <figure id="f0501539" figsize="col-wide">
                <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501539.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                         scalefitheight="232px"/>
                <caption>Figure 39. Installing New O-Ring</caption>
            </figure>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Locate the timing marks on the piston and sector shaft. Install the sector shaft
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501540">(Figure 40</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>The single timing mark on the sector tooth must line up between the two timing marks on
                            the piston rack. It may be necessary to tap the sector shaft with a soft hammer to insure
                            proper sector engagement.
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="f0501540" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501540.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 40. Install Sector Shaft</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the sector shaft cover and tighten the bolts to specification (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501541">Figure 41</hotlnk>). Refer to the
                    <hotlnk document="s05015y_39.xml" xrefid="x0501512">TORQUE CHART</hotlnk>
                    for the type of steering gear being serviced.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501541" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501541.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 41. Install Sector Shaft Cover</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the rubber boot over the sector shaft. Pack grease under the lip of the boot
                    before installation. For added seal protection, you may double boot the sector shaft as shown (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501542">Figure 42)</hotlnk>. To do so you must put one boot inside the other; do
                    not butt one against the other.
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501542" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501542.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 42. Double Boot Sector Shaft</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <para>
                <title>Severe Service Application</title>
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Pack the dirt excluder with grease and install it on the sector shaft. The lip of the
                    seal must face outward (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501543">Figure 43</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501543" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501543.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 43. Install Dirt Excluder</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Use a 2-1/2 inch seal driver to install the dirt excluder in the sector shaft cover
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501544">(Figure 44</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <figure id="f0501544" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501544.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 44. Installing Dirt Excluder</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the dust cover on the frame side of the sector shaft
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0501545">(Figure 45</hotlnk>).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Two types of dust covers are used on M-Series gears: a screw type or a stick-on type. When
                            using the stick-on type cover, clean the area with a suitable solvent and install using an
                            RTV material on the edge of the cover.
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="f0501545" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../figg05/G0501545.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="232px"/>
                    <caption>Figure 45. Install A Dust Cover</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install the pitman arm on the steering gear. Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s05015y_X0501511.xml" xrefid="x0501511">PITMAN ARM</hotlnk>
                    section.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Fill the system with an approved fluid and bleed the system if necessary. Refer to
                    <hotlnk document="s05015y_X0501509.xml" xrefid="x0501509">TYPES OF FLUID</hotlnk>
                    section for the type of vehicle being serviced.
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
